# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1911-new-york-highlanders-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The **1903 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1903.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and the Boston Americans as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first modern World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Americans defeated the Pirates, five games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the World Series, following the one-off 1900 *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first inter-league series since the 1890 World's Championship Series between the National League and defunct-since-1891 American Association.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 World Series would also mark the first championship series that is still celebrated today, as all previous series are considered pre-modern and these early contests are discussed by MLB and baseball historians separately.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] However, the 1903 arrangement was primarily between the two participating clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues, essentially making this season's World Series a voluntary event.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The defunct Baltimore Orioles were replaced by a new franchise in New York City known as the New York Highlanders; it was the last change to the lineup of AL and NL franchises until 1953.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would not return to Baltimore until the St.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns relocated there as a new Baltimore Orioles in 1954.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Orphans and Cleveland Bronchos were renamed as the Chicago Cubs and Cleveland Naps, respectively.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1901 season.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last season with this format, as the following season would see an increase of games played.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 16 with four teams playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 20, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Athletics and the Boston Americans.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 27, while the American League would see its final day of the season on September 29.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The inaugural World Series took place between October 1 and October 13.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (6 in AL, 9 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Americans defeating the Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1903 World Series in eight games.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Termed the "Battle of Ohio", the Cincinnati Reds and Cleveland Naps played an unofficial best of 11-game exhibition series after the regular season, with Cleveland winning the series six games to three.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the enfranchisement of the New York Highlanders, in place of the folded Baltimore Orioles, playing at Hilltop Park in New York City, New York, where they would play for ten seasons through 1912.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] On August 8, in what is known as the worst disaster in American sports spectating history, Black Saturday, a section of balcony at the Philadelphia Phillies' home at the Baker Bowl collapsed, killing 12 spectators and injuring 232.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies played the last 16 of their 61 home games at the home of the American League crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, Columbia Park from August 20.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The New York Highlanders' 1903 season was the team's first.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The team was founded as a replacement in the American League for the defunct Baltimore Orioles, was managed by Clark Griffith and played its home games at Hilltop Park (formally "American League Park").
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The club was at first officially the "Greater New York" baseball club, in deference to the established New York Giants, which were based in the Polo Grounds.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] This was the first season for the franchise that would be later known as the now-storied New York Yankees.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] They finished in 4th place in the AL with a record of 72–62.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] "Highlanders" was also originally short for "Gordon's Highlanders", a play on the name of the team President during 1903–1906, Joseph Gordon, along with the noted British military unit called The Gordon Highlanders.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The club was also derisively called "Invaders" in 1903, presumably by writers favorable to the Giants.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The New York press was creative with analogous nicknames for teams.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] In addition to "Highlanders", the team would soon acquire the alternate nickname "Yankees", the name that would soon become official and more famous among baseball fans in the coming decades.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] That word is a synonym for "American" in general, and short for American Leaguers or "Americans" in this case.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] Given the media's penchant for citing popular culture, that nickname was also possibly influenced by the then-current and hugely popular America-centric George M.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] Cohan Broadway play, "Little Johnny Jones", and its centerpiece song, "Yankee Doodle Dandy".
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] New York writers had similarly coined both the established nickname Brooklyn "[Trolley] Dodgers" and the nickname "Superbas" that the denizens of Flatbush carried for a while.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] As with the Highlanders, the latter was based on something unrelated, namely a circus act called "Hanlon's Superbas"; the Dodgers were managed by Ned Hanlon at that time.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] The 1904 New York Highlanders season, the team's second, finished with the team in second place in the American League with a record of 92–59.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] The team was managed by Clark Griffith and played home games at Hilltop Park.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] The casual use of that nickname suggests it was already in the popular lexicon, although "Highlanders" would continue to be the primary (and equally unofficial) nickname for several more years.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] The Highlanders were in the thick of the American League pennant race throughout the season, leading by two games as late as September 20.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] This led to the New York Giants announcement that they would not play in the World Series, since they considered the Highlanders to be only a "minor league" team.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] On the final day of the season at Hilltop Park, New York pitcher Jack Chesbro threw a wild pitch in the ninth inning, giving the Boston Americans the win, and the 1904 AL pennant.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] Even though it was Boston who stole the pennant on the final day, the Giants stuck to their word and their refusal prevented the World Series from being played.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] It would be a century later, in 2004, the next time Boston directly eliminated the Yankees from title contention, when they did so in the final game of the 2004 ALCS, a hundred years later in a repeat of sorts of the events of that year, the beginning of a long rivalry between the two clubs.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1905-new-york-highlanders-season] The 1905 New York Highlanders season was a season in American baseball.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1905-new-york-highlanders-season] The Highlanders finished in sixth place in the American League with a record of 71–78.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1905-new-york-highlanders-season] The team was managed by Clark Griffith and played its home games at Hilltop Park.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1906-new-york-highlanders-season] The 1906 New York Highlanders season, its fourth, finished with the team in second place in the American League with a record of 90–61.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1907-new-york-highlanders-season] The 1907 New York Highlanders season, the team's fifth, finished with the team in fifth place in the American League with a record of 70–78.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1907-new-york-highlanders-season] Another notable newcomer was New York's recently acquired left fielder Branch Rickey, who would become well known for integrating Jackie Robinson into the major leagues some four decades later.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] The 1908 New York Highlanders season finished with the team in eighth place in the American League with a record of 51–103.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] Their home games were played at Hilltop Park.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] The Highlanders finished in last place, 17 games out of seventh.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] It was the second-worst season in club history.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] Starting first baseman Hal Chase left the team in September under allegations that he was throwing games.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] After Clark Griffith's departure, the Highlanders lost 70 of their last 98 games under new manager Kid Elberfeld.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] On June 30, Cy Young of the Boston Red Sox threw a no-hitter against the Highlanders.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] In the game, Young had 3 hits and 4 RBI's.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] By now the alternate and equally unofficial nickname "Yankees" was being used frequently to refer to the Highlanders.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] *The New York Times* article about Young's no-hitter at "the American League Park" (Hilltop Park's formal name), referred to the club exclusively as "Yankees" throughout the article.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] Other newspapers continued to use the two nicknames interchangeably.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1908-new-york-highlanders-season] On September 4, 5 and 7, 1908, Walter Johnson of the Washington Senators shut out the Highlanders in three consecutive games.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1911-new-york-highlanders-season] The **1911 New York Highlanders season** saw the team finishing with a total of 76 wins and 76 losses, coming in sixth in the American League.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1911-new-york-highlanders-season] The alternate and equally unofficial nickname, "Yankees", was being used more and more frequently by the press.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1911-new-york-highlanders-season] Relations between the New York Highlanders and the enemy New York Giants seemed to be at a boiling point until a fateful April day when a fire destroyed the main portion of the grandstand at the Polo Grounds, the Giants' home field just a few blocks away (and downhill) from the Hilltop.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1911-new-york-highlanders-season] The Highlanders invited the Giants to play at Hilltop Park for the remainder of the 1911 season.
[src:1911-new-york-highlanders-season/1911-new-york-highlanders-season] Although the Giants were able to return to their partially rebuilt home two months later, this good deed would be remembered and returned to the Highlanders two years later.
